 In determining the relative amplitude of the input sine waves A and B, it has been stated earlier that this determination can be made in terms of the clipping level voltages V V V and V The pulse sequence of B +B is accomplished by coupling the B amplitude counter 18 to the flip-flop circuit 57 which receives inputs from the tunnel diode circuits 44 and 47, respectively, with the pulse output governed by the rate of reset from time base f Similarly, the pulse sequence A +A is determined by the A amplitude counter 20 coupled to the flip-flop circuit 59 which receives inputs from tunnel diode circuits 49 and 52. Again, the pulse output of A i-A is governed by the rate of reset time base i Since the period T counter 26 is coupled to the AND circuit 122 which has an input of f and the start-stop pulses, the period TN for N cycles is simply determined by the logical product of the start-stop line and the time base 7%; Knowing the period T, the ratio A/B can be calculated from Equation 4. 
 It should be noted with respect to the phase angle measurement that the region R and R definition will break down for large phase angles when the first B pulse occurs after the last A pulse. In practice, the definitions are adequate to the nominal angle of Interchanging signals A and B and inverting one of them, i.e., 180 phase shift, the range from 120 to 240 can be covered if the measured phase shift is substracted from 180. For the nominal range from to 300, one signal is inverted and its measured phase shift is added to 180. 
 In summary, the present invention is capable of high angular resolution since the signal errors in phase angle measurement are reduced by: (1) averaging over high frequency noise; (2) no dependence on the relative base line positions of the two sine waves; (3) compensation for base line drift at least to the extent that it can be linearly approximated; and (4) multiple averaging within one signal cycle as well as averaging over many cycles. Indeed, at ultra-low frequencies, multiple internal averaging can readily be increased thus reducing noise still further. 
 While there has been shown and described what is at present considered to be the preferred embodiment of the invention, modifications thereto will readily occur to those skilled in the art. It is not desired therefore that the invention be limited to those specific arrangements shown and described but it is to be understood that all equivalents, alterations and modifications within the spirit and scope of the present invention are meant to be included. 
